---
import Buffer from '../layouts/Buffer.astro';
import { siteConfig } from '../../site.config';

// TODO(owner): set/update this each time now.md's content actually changes.
const lastEdited = '2026-07-15';
---

<Buffer
  title={`now.md — ${siteConfig.name}`}
  description="What tanjal is building, learning, and reading right now."
  currentPath="/now"
>
  <div class="line">
    <p class="last-edited">
      <span class="last-edited-label">last edited:</span>
      <span class="last-edited-date">{lastEdited}</span>
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <h1>now.md</h1>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <h2 id="building">building</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <p>
      Working through a six-project arc in Rust and Go, aimed at {siteConfig.focus}. Currently on
      TODO(owner): name the current project (SPEC.md §14 item 4) — TODO(owner): one honest paragraph
      on where it stands.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <h2 id="learning">learning</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <p>
      The arc is forcing real fluency in Rust's ownership model and Go's concurrency primitives —
      the kind of thing that's easy to nod along to and hard to actually internalize without
      building something that breaks. The day job ({siteConfig.role}) feeds into this at most
      tangentially — TODO(owner): the one sentence, if there's a real connection worth naming.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <h2 id="reading">reading</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="line">
    <p>
      Currently about a third of the way through <em>{siteConfig.reading}</em>. Full log, queue, and
      finished books live on <a href="/library">library.md</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Buffer>

<style>
  .last-edited {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
  }

  .last-edited-label {
    color: var(--purple);
  }

  .last-edited-date {
    color: var(--orange);
  }
</style>
